snippet.textDisplay:
The first thing I noticed was the walking animation: it seems very robotic and doesn't seem to blend well with the environment; it's very rigid and tense. If you were to take everything completely away and just have the walking animation on a constant loop, it's the same rigid movements. One of the things I look for in a video game (especially a free moving game) is attention to detail and while I am aware that this game is still in development, the animations and combat style looks dull. When looking at games such as i.e. Helldivers II, a magazine reload will show that a magazine is dropped and stays on the ground for an X amount of time. Even here, enemies have the same death animations and disappear into a black mist instead of letting the corpses stay where they are to give the game's intentional "berserker" feel, such as a stack of corpses left by the protagonist.

Trying to give constructive criticism here but I believe this game still has a long way to go and if the company reads these comments, then there's my constructive criticism.

snippet.textDisplay: Well, the AI of the common enemies doesn't seem good. I'm sorry to say, but the combat feels slow. When you compare it to DS1, especially the hollows you fight on your way to Undeadburg, they have more attack patterns and become a real threat if you try to fight several at once. It all depends on the number and positioning of them that needs to be calculated to make it fair. Other points I notice is that the animation of dodging or rolling from attacks is a bit hard to identify, I think mainly because of the movement of your character, who doesn't seem to be able to turn 360 degrees without the movement of the camera. I'll also add that the fog in the place where the trailer takes place ends up creating a feeling of laziness in the construction of the environment. I understand that it serves to create the impression of an inhospitable place with really cruel weather conditions, but there need to be moments where you can see more of the world around you (especially when you're in high places and have the ability to observe distant lands) in order to have a good immersion. About the bosses shown, they didn't seem threatening to me, and I'm not saying that because of their appearance - which is great - but because of the speed of their movements and the long time between one attack and another. And I say this especially about the bear. Bears are very fast and strong animals and when they run towards you it's truly scary and I didn't feel the intensity or desire to kill this bear in the game.

snippet.textDisplay: The aesthetic of this game is beautiful, but was it just me or was everyone else waiting for something cool to happen. When you have games like Black Myth, and Elden Ring out already, games like these are going to have to bring the A game when showcasing. Nothing wrong with holding back a bit but sheesh I was bored. With a title like the first Berserker, there needs to be big death animations, limbs being removed, heavy aggression. We need to feel like we are just that. There weren't even any battle cries happening. I really hope they are just holding back, because otherwise it's just going to be another pin in the souls-like cushion. Take a look at Genndy Tartakovsky's Primal animation, that's how a Berserker should be, i have my fingers crossed.
